**Steps to Reproduce**:

Compile the following code:
```
using System;

ref struct S
{
    public Span<int> field;
}

static class E
{
    extension(S s)
    {
        public S Property { get => throw null!; set => throw null!; }
    }

    extension(ref S s)
    {
        public S RefReceiverProperty { get => throw null!; set => throw null!; }
    }

    public static void Test1(S s)
    {
        var x = new S {  field = stackalloc int[10] };
        s.Property = x; // error
        E.set_Property(s, x); // no errors

        s.RefReceiverProperty = x; // no errors
        E.set_RefReceiverProperty(ref s, x); // error
    }
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:

`CS8352`, `CS8350`

**Expected Behavior**:
The ref safety analysis doesn't depend on the syntax used to call the `set` accessors.
In both pairs of calls either the ref safety diagnostic is reported in both, or not reported in both.

**Actual Behavior**:
Compilation errors depend on the syntax used to call extension properties' set accessors despite producing equivalent IL code.

Following up on https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/pull/36454, see below for a minimal repro in which CS9236 (Compiling requires binding the lambda expression at least 200 times) is reported). Note that all lambdas have their parameter and return types explicitly determined, but CS9236 is still reported.

This reproed for me with dotnet SDK 10.0.100-preview.6.25358.103.

```c#
void Produces_a_diagnostic()
{
    AssertQuery(
        IQueryable<IQueryable<IQueryable<IQueryable<Customer>>>> (ISetSource ss) => ss.Set<Customer>()
            .Select(IQueryable<IQueryable<IQueryable<Customer>>> (Customer outer) => ss.Set<Customer>()
                .Select(IQueryable<IQueryable<Customer>> (Customer c) => ss.Set<Customer>()
                                                                                            // CS9236 just below
                    .Select(IQueryable<Customer> (Customer cc) => ss.Set<Customer>().OrderBy(string (Customer inner) => inner.CustomerID)))));

    void AssertQuery<TResult>(Func<ISetSource, IQueryable<TResult>> query)
        => throw new NotImplementedException();
}

// Interestingly, if I switch to a regular array with IEnumerable instead of IQueryable,
// the diagnostic goes away (possibly because of the removal of the extra Set() call?):
void Does_not_produce_a_diagnostic()
{
    AssertQuery(
        IEnumerable<IEnumerable<IEnumerable<IEnumerable<Customer>>>> (Customer[] ss) => ss
            .Select(IEnumerable<IEnumerable<IEnumerable<Customer>>> (Customer outer) => ss
                .Select(IEnumerable<IEnumerable<Customer>> (Customer c) => ss
                    .Select(IEnumerable<Customer> (Customer cc) => ss.OrderBy(string (Customer inner) => inner.CustomerID)))));

    void AssertQuery<TResult>(Func<Customer[], IEnumerable<TResult>> query)
        => throw new NotImplementedException();
}

public interface ISetSource
{
    IQueryable<TEntity> Set<TEntity>()
        where TEntity : class;
}

public class Customer
{
    public string CustomerID { get; set; }
}
```

